   1:Src/uart.c    **** /**
   2:Src/uart.c    ****  * uart.c — USART2 polling driver, 8N1
   3:Src/uart.c    ****  *
   4:Src/uart.c    ****  * Pins:
   5:Src/uart.c    ****  *   PA2  USART2_TX  AF7
   6:Src/uart.c    ****  *   PA3  USART2_RX  AF7
   7:Src/uart.c    ****  *
   8:Src/uart.c    ****  * Clock source selection (CCIPR register, bits [3:2] USART2SEL):
   9:Src/uart.c    ****  *   00 = PCLK1 (default after reset) — we use this.
  10:Src/uart.c    ****  *   PCLK1 = 80 MHz after SystemClock_Config().
  11:Src/uart.c    ****  *
  12:Src/uart.c    ****  * BRR calculation (OVER8 = 0 → oversampling by 16):
  13:Src/uart.c    ****  *
  14:Src/uart.c    ****  *   BRR = f_PCLK1 / baud
  15:Src/uart.c    ****  *
  16:Src/uart.c    ****  *   Example: baud = 115 200
  17:Src/uart.c    ****  *   BRR = 80 000 000 / 115 200 = 694.44 → 694  (truncation, not rounding)
  18:Src/uart.c    ****  *   Actual baud = 80 000 000 / 694 ≈ 115 274 bps  (error ≈ +0.064 %)
  19:Src/uart.c    ****  *   This is well within the UART ±2 % tolerance.
  20:Src/uart.c    ****  *
  21:Src/uart.c    ****  * Note: The ESP32-C6 is 3.3 V logic — direct connection is safe.
  22:Src/uart.c    ****  *       Cross-connect TX↔RX: STM PA2 → ESP32 RX, STM PA3 ← ESP32 TX.
  23:Src/uart.c    ****  */
  24:Src/uart.c    **** 
  25:Src/uart.c    **** #include "stm32l452xx.h"
  26:Src/uart.c    **** #include "uart.h"
  27:Src/uart.c    **** 
  28:Src/uart.c    **** void UART_Init(uint32_t baud)
  29:Src/uart.c    **** {
